Predicting Illegal Rentals in Philadlephia

Jessica Klion, Fay Walker, Angelica Kim

March 27, 2019

R Markdown

1.0 Introduction

1.1 How to use this document

This project was produced as part of the University of Pennsylvania Master of Urban Spatial Analytics Spring 2018 Practicum (MUSA 801). The following document presents an analysis of illegal rentals in Philadelphia and results in an interactive tool for the Philadelphia Department of Licenses and Inspections (L&I) that will ultimately help prioritize inspections in order to stymy illegal rentals before they turn into illegal evictions. The tool will provide a risk score for every rental property in the city, indicating each propertys likelihood of being rented illegally. This document includes a detailed overview of the use case, analysis and key findings, as well as the relevant code needed to replicate this analysis.

1.2 Abstract

Matthew Desmonds Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City shed light on the extent of the eviction crisis across the United States. In Philadelphia, rental prices have gone up by 10 percent in less than ten years and wages have not kept up. As a result, according to the United States Census, over half of renters are rent-burdened (qualifying as spending over one-third of salary on housing), and nearly one-third of these renters spend over 50 percent of their salary on housing. As more and more people are rent-burdened, evictions become more and more common, with failure to pay being the lead cause.

Evictions bear real downstream costs and implications, particularly because they impact single-mothers, low-income, and black households disproportionately. Additionally, eviction is a leading contributing cause of homelessness. In September 2017, Mayor Jim Kenney created the Mayors Task Force for Eviction Prevention and Response to further explore the over 24,000 evictions Philadelphia saw in 2016 alone. This number does not account for people who were illegally evicted, and while that number is unknown, in cities such as Milwaukee, including illegal evictions can double the total eviction rate.

Evictions refer to a legal process that provides tenants with rights. These rights mean that owners cannot lock tenants out of their homes, they must provide formal notice, and they must go through a court process to remove a tenant from a rental property. However, illegal evictions occur outside of this court process. In Philadelphia, to rent out a property, an owner must obtain a rental license, which requires, among other things, for the home to be up to code and safe to live in. Despite this requirement, thousands of homes in Philadelphia are rented without a license, which leaves the tenant with minimal protection. These illegal rentals can lack formal leases which allows the landlord to act on a whim, rather than by abiding to a formal process. This can lead to illegal evictions, which are particularly insidious because they leave tenants with limited legal recourse and protection. With no official record of the rental and the eviction, it is difficult to distill how often landlords are renting out their properties without a proper license.

Currently, Licenses and Inspections conducts inspections (which would identify illegal rentals) in an ad hoc fashion. There are limited inspectors and a backlog for inspections. Given this, L&I must be able to prioritize when and where they conduct inspections. The tool developed through this analysis predicts the probability that a property is being rented to a tenant without a rental license for all non-owner occupied homes in Philadelphia in order to help L&I better prioritize inspections.

1.3 Motivation

Between 2009 to 2016, rental prices in Philadelphia went up by 10 percent, while wages only went up by 0.3 percent. As a result, over half of Philly renters are rent-burdened (qualifying as spending over one-third of salary on housing), and nearly one-third of these renters spend over 50 percent of their salary on housing. As more and more people are rent-burdened, evictions become more and more common, with failure to pay being the lead cause of eviction. In 2016 alone, there were 24,000 evictions. Evictions bear real implications, particularly because they impact single-mothers, low-income, and black households disproportionately.

Evictions are a pressing issue in Philadelphia, so much so that Mayor Jim Kenney established the Mayors Task Force for Eviction Prevention and Response in September 2017, with the intention of developing an understanding of evictions in Philadelphia, determining best practices, identifying new funding streams to support task force activities, and producing a report and actionable recommendations to reduce evictions (Philadelphia Department of Health and Human Services, Mayors Task Force on Eviction Prevention and Response).

As rental prices rise and evictions become more frequent in the city, so too does homelessness. There are an estimated 5,700 homeless people in Philadelphia, and about 20 percent of people in shelters list eviction as a cause of homelessness.

Eviction is a legal process that provides tenants with rights. This means that owners cannot lock tenants out of their homes, they must provide notice, and they must go through the court process to remove a tenant from a rental property. In 2016, there were 24,000 evictions, accounting for 9 percent of households in Philadelphia (Mayors Task Force Report).

In Philadelphia, all rental units are required to be certified prior to leasing. Through certification, landlords must obtain a rental license. If a unit is not certified, but is still rented out, it is considered an illegal rental. In other words, a landlord is renting their units under the table, and as a result, the eviction process also happens under the table. Illegal rentals are dangerous because they leave tenants without legal recourse. If tenants are evicted from a property that is not licensed then they do not have to be given notice, and they cannot make their case in court.

With no official record of the rental and the eviction, it is difficult to distill how often landlords are renting out their properties without a proper license. These rentals without licenses pose a risk of not only illegal evictions, but also of code violations. In 2017, one in five eviction cases filed in Philadelphia was connected to a property where a code violation was issued within a year, potentially showing that there is value in examining the relationship between code violations and illegal rentals.

The only record we have for illegal rentals is of the Department of License and Inspections (L&I) Code Violation 9-3902; renting without a license, but this number is far underestimating the problem, and the 24,000 evictions Philly saw in 2016 does not account for illegal evictions. In cities such as Milwaukee, accounting for illegal evictions can increase eviction counts two-fold.

Currently, L&I conducts inspections in an ad hoc fashion. There are limited inspectors and a backlog for inspections. Given this, L&I must be able to prioritize when and where they conduct inspections, this tool will develop a model to predict the probability that a property is being rented to a tenant without a rental license for all non-owner occupied homes in Philadelphia in order to help L&I better prioritize inspections.

1.4 Methods in Brief
This analysis was built off of publicly available data, largely from Philadelphias open data website. Once gathered, we used feature engineering to create variables for our analysis. We then conducted an exploratory analysis of our data to better understand the nature of rentals, evictions, and illegal rentals in Philadelphia. Once all of our data was consolidated and cleaned we built a predictive model that provides an illegal rental risk score for all rental homes in Philadelphia.

1.5 Data
A primary challenge in this analysis was creating one cohesive dataset based off of disparate and unstandardized administrative data. To develop this dataset we pulled data from the following sources:

  • Licensing and Inspection Code Violations (from Licenses and Inspections via OpenDataPhilly)
  • Business Licenses (from Licenses and Inspections via OpenDataPhilly)
  • Property Assessments (from the Office of Property Assessment via OpenDataPhilly)
Additional data was collected that inform both our exploratory analysis and our model development. This included the following data:
  • Docket of Eviction Cases 2014-2016 (from Community Legal Aid Services)
  • Tax Delinquency (via OpenDataPhilly)
  • Socioeconomic and Demographic Data (2012-2016 American Community Survey)

Data and Data Sources

2.0 Data Wrangling and Cleaning
The following presents an overview of how we developed a cohesive dataset from the many necessary datasets for our analysis. This process required extensive work to ultimately get a dataset that is usable and manageable.

2.1 Data Cleaning

Office of Property Assessment (OPA) Data
The final dataset for this analysis includes all potentially rental properties in Philadelphia. To create this dataset, we began with the Office of Property Assessment data, which includes information on every parcel in Philadelphia. The full dataset from 2018 included over 600,000 rows. To cull it down to just residential rental properties, we began by selecting out the rows where parcels were zoned residential. This cut the dataset down to about 500,000 observations. The following zoning categories were kept in the dataset:
  • Residential single-family detached homes (RSD)
  • Residential single-family attached districts (RSA)
  • Residential two-family attached districts (RTA)
  • Residential multi-family districts (RM)
  • Residential mixed-use districts (RMX)

Following this cut, which provides a dataset of residential parcels in Philadelphia, the OPA dataset was further cut down to exclude known owner-occupied properties. While the designation of owner-occupied homes is not explicitly included in the OPA dataset, it could be proxied. For this analysis, owner occupied homes were proxied as those that received a homestead exemption tax break, which is included in the OPA data. This cut the dataset down to about 300,000 rows.

For this analysis, the OPA dataset served as our primary datasource and where we derived the majority of features for our model. Once cleaned, all of our datasets were joined to this dataset as it was the largest.

Business License Data
The business license data included about 300,000 unique observations for every business license issued by the City of Philadelphia for over 10 years, with some data going back as far as 2000. The dataset included information on license type, license status, license issue date, and license holder. The first step in managing this dataset was to limit the data to just 2016 to 2018. From there, we further cut the data down by selecting out those rows where a residential rental license was issued. This cut the data down to about 160,000 rows. Note that this vacant residential properties were left in the dataset. Unneeded columns were removed from this dataset and then it was ready to join to the OPA dataset.

Office of License and Inspections Violations Data
The data on violations from L&I included over 1 million unique observations for every violation that the office had issued since 2007. This dataset is particularly important for our analysis because it contains the independent variable for our model: illegal rental violation (code: 9-3902). In addition to this information, this dataset included information on when violations were issued, who they were issued to, and violations status. Like with the business license data, the first step in managing this dataset was to limit the dataset to only years to 2016-2018. This left us with 340,684 observations. Before joining, but following feature engineering, we cut the dataset down so that each row represented one property. In other words, for those properties that had multiple violations, we selected out just one row, so that our join would work. In performing this cut after feature engineering, we were able to capture if a property had multiple violations, as we included a feature for total number of violations. From there, unneeded columns were removed and the data was ready to join.

Tax Delinquency Data
The tax delinquency dataset included about 45,000 unique observations and represents the properties in Philadelphia where the owner is delinquent on their taxes. In other words, the dataset indicates where a homeowner is behind on their property taxes. This dataset shows tax delinquency for 2017 (confirm). The dataset required minimal cleaning and was ready to join to OPA without cutting rows.

United States Census Data
This dataset contained demographic information from the American Community Survey using 2013-2017 census tract level data. It is worth noting that this is our only data that is not a the parcel level. We pulled the following demographics that we deemed of interest:
  • Percent foreign-born
  • Percent black
  • Percent non-white
  • Percent renters
  • Percent High rent-burden
  • Percent below-poverty level
  • Percent single-mother households
  • Elevated Blood Lead Level Indicators (this was pulled from OpenData, not from the Census, but it was gathered at the tract level and joined to the census csv)

Court Docket Data
The court docket data includes all eviction cases in the City of Philadelphia from 2016 to 2018. The docket included extensive information regarding each eviction case, including plaintiff and defendant, case data, and case status. We removed unnecessary columns from the dataset prior to joining with the rest of our data.

Azavea Neighborhoods
The final dataset included in our analysis was a spatial dataset of neighborhoods in Philadelphia. This provides spatial information on neighborhood boundaries and required no cleaning prior to joining. However, this dataset is useful in both our exploratory analysis and in our spatial model.

Prior to joining the datasets to the OPA dataset, we had to do some additional cleaning Importantly, we had to identify and remove the NAs and missing information from each column. To do so, we first calculated where the NAs and missing data were and then made a fixed effect for each variable with missing information, which accounts for the fact that we do not have information on this variable for this property. We then made the missing information and NAs zero in each column where they existed, as the model needs data to run.

2.2 Data Wrangling
We then proceeded as follows to join the numerous datasets together:

  • Join 1: Left Joined OPA Dataset with our L&I licensing dataset. Used OPA Account number as unique ID.
  • Join 2: Left Joined L&I violation dataset to Join 1. Included all violations. Used OPA Account number as unique ID.
  • Join 3: Left Joined tax delinquency with Join 2. Included all tax delinquent. Used OPA Account number as unique ID.
  • Join 4: Spatially joined census geometries to Join 3.
  • Join 5: Left joined census tract level demographics to Join 4 using FIPS as unique ID.
  • Join 6: Left joined docket data to join 5 by ARC_Address (street address only, not counting units, not case-sensitive).
  • Join 7: Spatially joined neighborhood geometries to Join 6.

Note that because the final dataset is a product of numerous other datasets, NAs were introduced during the joining process. This occured where a parcel lacked data from one of the datasets joined to OPA. For example, if a parcel has never had an L&I violation, columns from the L&I dataset would have NA for that row. As a result, once all of the datasets were joined together, another round of cleaning occured. NAs were changed to zero fixed effects were created. In addition, extra columns were removed. Once the cleaning was complete, we were left with a dataset of about 306,000 rows with over 200 variables.

3.0 Exploratory Analysis
Our exploratory analysis focuses on understanding the rental market in Philadelphia, with a primary focus on evictions, rentals, and illegal rentals. Through our exploratory analysis, we intend to answer the following questions:

  • Where are residential rental properties in Philadelphia?
  • Where are evictions in Philadelphia, and how has that changed over time?
  • Where are illegal rentals in Philadelphia, what types of properties are being illegally rented, how has that changed over time?

These questions helped to guide our understanding of renting in Philadelphia, and, in particular, our understanding of illegal renting in the City.

Where are residential rental properties in Philadelphia?

Philadelphia has 303,592 potential rental properties according to OPA data. This number was determined by extracting from the OPA dataset all rows that are zoned residential that did not receive a homestead tax exemption (which we are using as a proxy for owner occupation of a residence). The following map shows potential rentals by neighborhood.

Rentals by neighborhood in Philadelphia

As the map shows, rentals are most common in West Philadelphia and North Philadelphia, with a high percentage of rentals just over the Schuylkill River, south of Center City. When examining the active rental licenses at the neighborhood level, additional nuance can be seen. While rental licenses are well dispersed throughout the city, inactive licenses are more concentrated in North and Northeast Philadelphia.

Where are evictions in Philadelphia, and how has that changed over time?

Evictions by neighborhood in Philadelphia

Between 2016 and 2018, there were about 55,700 evictions in the City. Understanding where legal evictions are occurring is beneficial for understanding the nature of the rental market in Philadelphia, which ultimately provides insights into illegal rentals.

The map below shows evictions by neighborhood between 2016-2018. Rather than showing a count of evictions, we instead chose to display evictions as a percentage in order to normalize the data and account for neighborhoods with higher or lower rental totals. As the map shows, evictions were concentrated in North and Northeast Philadelphia, as well as West Philadelphia. In general, these evictions were concentrated in lower-income, minority areas, which is consistent with findings from the report of homelessness produced by the mayors taskforce.

Where are illegal rentals in Philadelphia, how has that changed over time, and what types of properties are being illegally rented?

Illegal rentals by neighborhood in Philadelphia

Our exploratory analysis of illegal rentals in Philadelphia focused on several aspects of illegal rentals. Between 2010 and 2019, there were 7,428 citations given out by L&I inspectors to individuals renting their property illegally. This number indicates all of the illegal rentals the city is aware of, however, it is a proxy for illegal rentals. The real number of illegal rentals cannot be officially captured. The number of illegal rentals by year increased between 2016 and 2018. Of these citations, about 77 percent were for one and two family homes, 21 percent were multi-family units, and about 2 percent were for rooms in houses. This distribution is unsurprising given the distribution of housing typologies in Philadelphia. Because Philadelphia is a city of row-homes, not high-rises; it would make sense that there would be one and two family homes with illegal rental citations.

The map above shows illegal rentals by neighborhood as a percentage of total rentals by neighborhood. As the map shows, at the neighborhood level, illegal rentals comprise almost zero percent of total rentals, however, in some neighborhoods they comprise over one percent of rentals. Additionally, illegal rentals do not follow the same pattern as evictions. The highest neighborhood wide concentrations are in and around Center City and West Philadelphia, as opposed to the evictions we saw more in northern and eastern north Philadelphia.

Notably, the number of illegal rentals by year is very consistent. In 2016, there were 2,196 citations for illegal rentals. In 2017, there were 2,243 citations for illegal rentals, and in 2018, there were 2,337 citations for illegal rentals. While the number has gone up each year, the rate of change is minimal.

Further, analysis of the code violation data indicates that some properties and property owners had multiple violations, as shown in the tables below. In all, about 1,000 landlords and about 900 properties appeared more than once in the illegal rental dataset, which accounts for, why, of the over 7,000 illegal rentals we saw, there was only about 3,000 separate parcels with illegal eviction violations.

3.2 Feature Engineering
OPA
Aside from basing our base dataset off of OPA we also used housing characteristics variables to create a litany of engineers factor variables ranging from square footage to number of bathrooms. We also used OPA data to determine whether or not the property had an absentee landlord by creating variables based off of rows that had different mailing addresses and parcel addresses for tax mailing. Of these absentee landlords we also create variables based off of whether landlords were located in the greater Philly area (NJ or DE), or whether they were out-of-region. We created these variables based on the assumption that if a landlord is not physically present it would make it more difficult for them to maintain their paperwork and licensing in order.

Licenses
We used the license information to create variables based on whether properties had been rented in this past. This meant we created variables that determined whether licenses were active or inactive, if they were inactive when had they expired, and how many licenses the specific parcel has had in the past. Together this shows us whether a property has been rented in the past, and if so, whether it is still rented, or has lapsed. In addition, we used K nearest neighbor to determine average distance of each property to its 5 nearest rental licenses.

Violations
Our independent variable that we are predicting is the likelihood that a unit is being illegally rented. Arguably, whether the property has a past violation for illegally renting is thereby one of our most important values. Illegal rental violations are comprised of four different codes:
  • 9-3902 (1) - 1 and 2 family homes
  • 9-3902 (2) - multi-family homes
  • 9-3902 (3) - rooming unit or house
  • 9-3902 (4) - hotels

Hotels represented only a few individual records and for the purposes of this analysis, were excluded. Using the other three violation codes only resulted in a dataset of about 7,500 properties who received citations for illegally renting. Because hotels only account for about 5 illegal rentals, getting rid of hotels did not notably change our data. Note that using the L&I violation of renting without a license is only a proxy for illegal rentals. It is likely that there are more illegal rentals in this city, but for the purposes of this analysis, this proxy will suffice.

Additionally, from this dataset we were able to create variables that tell us:
  • Length of time since last violation
  • Number of violations at a home
  • Kind of violation (interior/exterior)
  • Violations status
  • Average distance to five nearest violations (using K-nearest neighbor)

In creating these variables we are operating under the assumption that if a landlord is likely to receive one violation that this may be an indicator of other kinds of violations (in this case, illegal rentals).

Tax Delinquency
The tax delinquency dataset required minimal feature engineering. The dataset already included a variable on the amount owed. We created one variable that calculated the number of years delinquent, and one binary variable set to 1 for all tax delinquent properties so that when joined back to the larger dataset we can easily identify the delinquent properties.

Tax delinquency by neighborhood in Philadelphia

There are approximately 25,000 tax delinquent parcels in Philadelphia. These homes are primarily located in central northern Philadelphia and west Philadelphia, accounting for up to twelve percent of parcels in some neighborhoods.

Census
There is extensive research on who is disproportionately impacted by eviction. We wanted to see if these demographic characteristics were also linked to illegal rentals in Philadelphia. Because we could selected from the census which variables we wanted, minimal feature engineering was not required for this dataset.

Docket
For the docket data, we wanted to determine, who are the repeat offenders and where are there properties evicting multiple families. In order to do this we aggregated evictions by landlord and by address in order to come up with a count. We then joined this data back to the original file so that every row has a landlord_evict_count and a property_evict_count.

4.0 Modeling strategy
An important part of our project is predicting events where there is no data. Because we are reliant on existing data, it is very possible that our model would be overfit for predicting homes that already have violations, meaning that homes that have never interacted with L&I would be underpredicted. Because certain data would be overpowering in our model, largely the violations data, resulting in overfitting of the model, we used an ensemble approach to modeling. In doing so, we created three unique stories, a housing story, a demographic story, and a geospatial story. The housing story included data on home characteristics, violations, and evictions; the geospatial story included data on neighborhoods and distance to key factors; the demographic model included relevant census data. These models were strung together to create one model that captured all three stories. The model was validated using several metrics to ensure it is both accurate and generalizable.

Which variables correlate with each other?

To get a better understanding of the relationship between variables, we developed correlation matrices (corplots) for the three separate stories. Through the corplots, we are able to gain a better understanding of which independent variables are colinear, which is important for model building. The below corplot, for the geospatial model, shows that of the variables included, average distance to the five nearest rental licenses and average distance to the five nearest code violations are positively correlated with each other.

Geospatial Model Corplot

How do variables compare between properties with and without an illegal rental violation?
In addition to corplots, to gain a better understanding of the characteristics of properties that have been rented illegally and properties that have not provides helps with building models. In instances where the characteristics of homes are different between the two categories, it is likely that these variables will be strong predictors in our models. Summary statistics for selected variables for two subsets of our data, where illegal rentals have occurred and where illegal rentals have not occured, are shown below.

Summary Statistics of Selected Variables (Illegal Rentals)

Summary Statistics of Selected Variables (non-Illegal Rentals)

As the tables shows, the count of evictions each landlord has had, the number of years a property is tax delinquent, and the number of code violations a property has received are all distributed differently across the two categories. Unsurprisingly, the mean landlord eviction count is greater in the subset of data where there has not been a citation for an illegal eviction. This is unsurprising given that eviction is a legal process only afforded to landlords who rent their properties legally. Conversely, the mean of number of years owed in taxes is higher in the illegal rental category. Surprisingly, the count of violations per property owner has a higher mean in the non-illegal rental category. While this does not indicate that there were not code violations in the illegal rental category, it indicates that property owners renting out their properties legally also have code violations, or have previously had a code violation.

4.1 Model Building
We created three different models that will be ensembled, or joined, together to create one final model that will predict the likelihood that a residential rental property will be rented illegally, that is without a license. The three models were created include a:
  • Housing model
  • Geospatial model
  • Demographic model

The housing model included data from the OPA dataset on housing characteristics, data on violations at the parcel level, data on rental licenses at the parcel level, and tax delinquency data at the parcel level. The geospatial model included only geospatial variables, and the demographic data from the census. For all three models, the dependent variable is a binary for had illegal rental violation. We trained the models on a dataset that included confirmed illegal rentals. The models will ultimately be tested on the remainder of the dataset, which includes every additional residential rental property in Philadelphia, all of which are not confirmed to have been rented illegally.

Initially, we used a logistic regression for our prediction. To add more power to our prediction, we tested a random forest and XGBoost models.

4.2 Validation
To validate our models, measured goodness of fit. This allowed us to compare predictions across several models, ultimately helping us determine which variables should be included in a final model for each story. This method can also be used in later iterations of visualize predictions across different classes. The below provides an example of how this validation was run.

geo_fit1 <- glm(illegalRental2.1 ~ ., data = Finaldat_Geo %>% 
                     dplyr::select(-knn_viol_5, -knn_lic_5, -MAPNAME),
                   family="binomial"(link="logit"))

testSetProbsgeo1 <- 
  data.frame(class = geoTrain$illegalRental2.1,
             probs = predict(geo_fit1, geoTrain, type="response")) %>%
  mutate(predClass = as.factor(ifelse(probs >= 0.50 ,1,0))) 

head(testSetProbsgeo1)

At this stage, however, the predictions were not as expected, with the model predicting that every single property in the dataset has a 100 percent chance of being rented illegally. This indicates an issue with the dataset at large that must be resolved prior to any continuation of model building.

5.0 Next Steps
After determining why our models are not running as anticipated, the next step in our model development is to improve the existing stories we have created through additional feature engineering and ensembling. We will also test out using random forest and XGBoost to improve the power of our model.

Importantly, we will also focus more on validation of our models. Validation measures we intend to examine include sensitive, specificity, AUC, and ROC. We also intend to conduct tests of spatial validation to determine if our model is both accurate and generalizable across the city. One way of doing such testing is to test the model by neighborhood and map the predictions or average error to see if there is any spatial variation in the accuracy of the predictions.

Down the road, we will also develop a wire-frame for a web-application that L&I inspectors will able able to use to better prioritize home inspections.

#KNN violations and licenses
#KNN FUNCTION
nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint)
  
  return(output)  
}

mapTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(face="italic"),

    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2)
  )
}
